INSERT INTO book_settings (key, value) VALUES
  ('book_title',    'Less Work. More Impact\nIn Economic Development'),
  ('book_subtitle', 'The Economic Developer''s Secret to Focusing on Impact, Not Busywork'),
  ('book_hero_desc','A practical guide for economic developers ready to stop being buried in preparation work and start creating real impact. Written by Eric Kleinsorge after three decades in the field.'),
  ('author_name',   'Eric Kleinsorge'),
  ('author_title',  'CEO/Chairman, Global Site Location Industries · Founder, EconSquad AI'),
  ('author_bio',    'Eric Kleinsorge has spent more than three decades in economic development and site location. As CEO of Global Site Location Industries and founder of EconSquad AI, he has helped communities compete for investment, talent, and opportunity across the country. This book distills what he learned about protecting focus, eliminating busywork, and operating at the level that actually creates impact — not just activity.'),
  ('chapter_count', '16'),
  ('free_chapters',  '1'),
  ('ch1_title', 'The Busywork Tax in Economic Development'),
  ('ch1_desc',  'Economic development does not suffer from a lack of effort.'),
  ('ch1_lead',  'Economic development does not suffer from a lack of effort.'),
  ('ch1_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch1_body',  '<p>Economic development does not suffer from a lack of effort. It suffers from a lack of leverage. Most economic developers didn''t enter the profession expecting to spend their days drafting documents, rewriting content, or starting from scratch on routine work. They entered the field because they wanted to shape communities, attract investment, build relationships, and create long-term impact. Yet, somewhere along the way, busywork became normalized. Writing a first draft feels productive. Researching a company feels necessary. Summarizing meetings feels responsible. Individually, these tasks seem harmless. Collectively, they create a tax; a quiet drain on impact, energy, and focus that compounds every week. This is the Busywork Tax. The Busywork Tax is not about laziness or inefficiency. It''s about misalignment. Highly compensated professionals routinely spend their effort on work that does not require their expertise, judgment, or experience. Because this work is familiar and visible, it often crowds out the work that actually drives results. The danger isn''t that economic developers are busy. The danger is that they are busy creating instead of executing. Execution is where outcomes happen. It is where relationships are built, deals move forward, and communities win projects. But execution requires focus, uninterrupted, high-impact attention. That focus is constantly being consumed by tasks that could be handled differently. The Busywork Tax also has a hidden emotional cost. When professionals feel overwhelmed, they default to work they can control. Drafting a document feels safer than making a call. Editing content feels easier than following up with a prospect. Over time, this shifts behavior away from impact and toward comfort. This isn''t a failure of discipline. It''s a failure of system design. Economic development organizations rarely design workflows around protecting high-impact work. They design around responsiveness, completeness, and optics. The result is staff that look busy, feel exhausted, and struggle to move faster than the workload. Less Work. More Impact starts with recognizing this tax and acknowledging that doing everything yourself is not a badge of honor. It''s a bottleneck. The rest of this book is about removing that bottleneck. CHAPTER TWO Why Hiring More People Doesn''t Fix the Problem When economic development organizations feel overwhelmed,</p>'),
  ('ch2_title', 'Why Hiring More People Doesn''t Fix the Problem'),
  ('ch2_desc',  'the instinctive response is almost always the same: we need more people.'),
  ('ch2_lead',  'the instinctive response is almost always the same: we need more people.'),
  ('ch2_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch2_body',  '<p>the instinctive response is almost always the same: we need more people. More staff often feels like the responsible answer. More hands should mean more capacity, and more capacity should mean more progress. But in practice, hiring more people rarely solves the underlying problem. In many cases, it makes it worse. The reason is simple: most economic development organizations don''t have a capacity problem; they have an impact allocation problem. Adding people to a system that already misallocates effort doesn''t eliminate the Busywork Tax; it spreads it. New hires are quickly absorbed into the same workflows that already drain senior staff. They inherit the same expectations, the same reactive culture, and the same belief that productivity means creating more emails, documents, reports, and drafts, rather than executing on the work that moves projects forward. Over time, organizations find themselves with more people, higher payroll, and little increase in actual impact. This creates a dangerous illusion. Leaders look at headcount and assume leverage has been added. In reality, they''ve simply multiplied the cost of inefficiency. There''s also a hidden cost that rarely gets discussed: senior focus leakage. Every new hire requires onboarding, supervision, correction, and reviewing. Experienced economic developers that are paid for judgment and relationships, end up spending even more effort reviewing work, fixing drafts, and managing output quality. The very people whose focus should be most protected become the final checkpoint for everything created downstream. The result is a paradox: the more people you hire, the more stretched your senior staff can become. This problem is especially acute in economic development because so much of the work is ambiguous. RFIs are different every time. Outreach requires nuance. Board communication must be tailored. These tasks don''t lend themselves easily to rigid delegation. So instead of being offloaded, they are shared, and shared work often defaults back to the most experienced person in the room. Hiring also introduces political and financial friction. Budgets increase. Boards scrutinize payroll. Expectations rise. And once a position is created, it''s difficult to remove, even if the role doesn''t produce the leverage that was promised. What''s often missing from the hiring conversation is a more fundamental question: What work should we not be doing at all? Many organizations hire to keep up with volume rather than redesigning how work flows. They respond to pressure instead of eliminating the root cause. And because busywork feels productive, it goes unquestioned. The most effective organizations take a different approach. Before hiring, they ask: Which tasks consume the most effort? Which ones truly require human judgment? Which tasks are repetitive, predictable, or first-draft work? Where are highly paid professionals acting as content creators instead of decision-makers? These questions don''t lead immediately to hiring decisions. They lead to workflow redesign. In many cases, the real opportunity isn''t adding people--it''s removing unnecessary creation work from the plates of those who already exist. When senior staff stop drafting, summarizing, and reworking from scratch, capacity for higher-impact work appears without adding headcount. This doesn''t mean organizations should never hire. It means hiring should come after focus has been protected, not before. Less Work. More Impact is not about squeezing more output from fewer people. It''s about ensuring the right people are doing the right work at the right level. When that alignment exists, hiring becomes strategic instead of reactive and growth becomes sustainable instead of exhausting. CHAPTER THREE What Economic Developers Are Actually Paid to Do Economic developers are not paid for effort.</p>'),
  ('ch3_title', 'What Economic Developers Are Actually Paid to Do'),
  ('ch3_desc',  'They are paid for judgment.'),
  ('ch3_lead',  'They are paid for judgment.'),
  ('ch3_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch3_body',  '<p>They are paid for judgment. They are paid to interpret complex situations, balance competing interests, build trust with decision-makers, and advance opportunities forward in environments where outcomes are uncertain and timelines are long. Their value is not measured by how much they produce, but by the quality of the decisions they help shape and the momentum they help create. And yet, much of an economic developer''s day is spent doing work that does not require judgment at all. This disconnect is at the heart of the impact problem. To understand how effort gets misallocated, it helps to separate work into two very different categories: value execution and value creation. Value Execution: The Work Only Humans Can Do Value execution is where economic developers create real impact. This is the work that requires experience, context, and credibility. It includes: Building and maintaining relationships with prospects, partners, and community leaders Interpreting signals from companies and site selectors. Making trade-offs between incentives, workforce realities, and long-term goals Guiding projects through political, financial, and organizational complexity Following up, negotiating, persuading, and aligning stakeholders. This work is nuanced. It is situational. It cannot be scripted or automated without losing effectiveness. It is also the work that directly drives outcomes. When economic developers have the focus to execute well, projects move faster. Conversations deepen. Opportunities compound. Value Creation: The Work That Consumes Effort but Rarely Creates Impact Value creation work looks productive on the surface, but it is fundamentally different. This category includes: Writing first drafts of documents and emails Researching companies, industries, or competitors Summarizing meetings or background materials Creating board updates and reports from scratch Reformatting, rewording, and rewriting content This work is necessary, but it is not where expertise is applied. It does not require senior-level judgment. And when it absorbs too much effort, it crowds out execution. The problem isn''t that value creation work exists. The problem is that it defaults upward. In many organizations, the most experienced person becomes the default creator. Not because they should be, but because they can do it quickly and correctly. Over time, this creates a dangerous inversion: the more capable someone is, the more low-impact work they absorb. This is how high performers become bottlenecks. The Hidden Cost of Creation Creation work has a deceptive quality. It feels safe. It feels controlled. It produces visible output. But it carries a hidden cost: opportunity loss. Every hour spent drafting is an hour not spent following up. Every hour spent researching is an hour not spent building trust. Every hour spent rewriting is an hour not spent advancing a project. Because outcomes in economic development are often delayed, it''s easy to miss this cost. The work gets done. The inbox stays full. The calendar stays booked. But momentum quietly stalls. Over time, organizations normalize this imbalance. Being busy becomes proof of value. Exhaustion becomes a badge of honor. And execution, the very thing economic developers are hired to do, gets squeezed into the margins. Why This Misalignment Persists This misallocation of effort isn''t caused by poor discipline or weak leadership. It''s caused by systems that reward responsiveness and completeness over impact. Economic developers are expected to: Respond quickly. Be thorough. Look prepared. Control quality. Without intentional design, these expectations pull professionals into creation work by default. There is no guardrail that says, this task does not require your level of expertise. As a result, effort gets spent where it is easiest to measure, not where it creates the most impact. Less Work. More Impact Starts Here Less Work. More Impact does not start with tools or technology. It starts with clarity. Clarity about what work deserves your attention. Clarity about what work does not. Clarity about where judgment matters and where it does not. When economic developers clearly distinguish execution from creation, a powerful shift happens. They begin to protect their focus not out of selfishness, but out of responsibility. They recognize that doing everything themselves is not commitment--it''s misallocation. This clarity is the foundation for everything that follows in this book. In the next chapter, we''ll explore the most damaging misconception of all: the belief that creating more is the same as executing better--and why separating those two is the key to unlocking real leverage. CHAPTER FOUR Creating vs. Executing One of the most damaging misconceptions in economic</p>'),
  ('ch4_title', 'Creating vs. Executing'),
  ('ch4_desc',  'development is the belief that creating more work is the same as executing better.'),
  ('ch4_lead',  'development is the belief that creating more work is the same as executing better.'),
  ('ch4_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch4_body',  '<p>development is the belief that creating more work is the same as executing better. It isn''t. Creation and execution are not interchangeable; they require different skills, produce different outcomes, and place very different demands on focus. Confusing the two leads to busy calendars, full inboxes, and stalled impact. Understanding the difference between creating and executing is one of the most important mindset shifts an economic development professional can make. Creation Is About Producing Inputs Creation work is about producing inputs. It includes drafting documents, gathering information, summarizing discussions, outlining plans, and preparing materials. Creation turns blank pages into usable outputs. This work is necessary. No execution happens without inputs. But creation has a ceiling: once the input exists, its value stops growing until action is taken. Creation is also finite. A draft is either written or it isn''t. A report is either completed or it isn''t. Because of this, creation work feels satisfying. It provides closure. It produces something tangible. And that''s exactly why it can become addictive. Execution Is About Producing Outcomes Execution is different. Execution is about movement. It''s about applying judgment, building alignment, navigating resistance, and pushing work forward despite uncertainty. Execution includes: Following up when it''s uncomfortable Advancing conversations without perfect information Aligning stakeholders with competing interests Making decisions that don''t have obvious right answers Staying engaged long after the document is finished Execution is open-ended and rarely feels complete. There is no final draft of a relationship or a negotiation. Progress is measured in momentum, not outcomes on paper. Because execution is more ambiguous and harder to measure, it is easier to postpone. Why Creation Crowds Out Execution In most organizations, creation work crowds out execution not because it is more important, but because it is more controllable. When faced with uncertainty, professionals default to tasks they can finish. Writing a document feels productive even when it does not move a project forward. Editing a report feels safer than making a difficult call. Over time, this creates a subtle but powerful shift: effort is spent where activity is visible, not where impact is actually created. In economic development, this is especially dangerous. Projects are won through persistence, trust, and timing--not through perfectly written materials. But because those factors are harder to quantify, they are often undervalued. The First-Draft Trap One of the biggest execution killers is the first-draft trap. Highly capable professionals often take on first drafts because they can complete them faster and better than anyone else. But every first draft written by a senior economic developer is effort taken away from high-impact execution. The issue isn''t skill. It''s leverage. A first draft is an input. It is not the outcome. When senior staff repeatedly create inputs, they become the slowest part of the system. Execution waits. Follow-up gets delayed. Opportunities go cold. The organization looks busy, but impact stalls. Execution Requires Space Execution cannot be rushed; it requires thinking time, relationship time, and follow-through time. None of those survive in a calendar dominated by creation work. When calendars are filled with drafting, revising, and preparing, execution is forced into the margins, early mornings, late evenings, and mental leftovers. This is not sustainable. And it''s not why economic developers were hired. Rebalancing the Equation The goal is not to eliminate creation work. The goal is to decouple creation from execution. When creation work is handled efficiently, consistently, and without consuming senior judgment, execution expands naturally. Focus increases. Clarity improves. Momentum builds. The most effective economic developers are not those who create the most; they are those who execute with the greatest impact. They protect their focus not because they are unwilling to work, but because they understand that execution is fragile. It only happens when space exists for it. Why This Distinction Matters Until creation and execution are clearly separated, no tool, hire, or system will fully solve the problem. Creation will continue to expand to fill available effort. Execution will remain reactive. This distinction is the turning point. Once economic developers see creation for what it is (necessary but low-impact) they can begin to redesign how work flows through their organization. In the next chapter, we''ll examine the true cost of doing it yourself and why personal efficiency is often the enemy of organizational effectiveness. CHAPTER FIVE The True Cost of Doing It Yourself "I can do it faster myself."</p>'),
  ('ch5_title', 'The True Cost of Doing It Yourself'),
  ('ch5_desc',  'This phrase is one of the most common and most costly assumptions in economic development.'),
  ('ch5_lead',  'This phrase is one of the most common and most costly assumptions in economic development.'),
  ('ch5_time',  '6 min read'),
  ('ch5_body',  '<p>This phrase is one of the most common and most costly assumptions in economic development. On the surface, it sounds practical. Experienced professionals can write faster, research more efficiently, and produce higher-quality work than most alternatives. Doing it yourself often feels like the quickest path to getting things done. But speed at the task level is not the same as speed at the outcome level. When economic developers default to doing it themselves, they may save minutes in the moment, but they lose impact across hours, days, and sometimes months in the broader arc of execution. This is the true cost of doing it yourself. Efficiency at the Wrong Level Most economic developers are personally efficient. That''s how they earned their roles. They know how to get things done. They pride themselves on responsiveness and quality. The problem is not inefficiency; it is misplaced efficiency. When senior professionals apply their efficiency to low-impact creation work, they starve the system of what only they can provide: judgment, follow-through, and momentum. An hour saved by writing something yourself rarely translates into impact elsewhere. More often, it displaces execution work that simply never happens. The Opportunity Cost No One Sees Opportunity cost is inherently invisible. You don''t see the call that wasn''t made. You don''t track the follow-up that got delayed. You don''t measure the relationship that cooled because attention was elsewhere. But those missed moments are where economic development outcomes are decided. Projects don''t fail because documents weren''t drafted; they fail because conversations stall, signals were missed, and timing slipped. Those failures rarely point back to effort spent creating, but they almost always trace back to impact not created through execution. Doing it yourself feels productive. Not focusing on the right work is expensive. The Comfort Trap There''s also an emotional dimension to doing it yourself. Creation work is comfortable and familiar. It allows professionals to feel in control, especially when outcomes are uncertain. When projects stall or pressure rises, it''s natural to retreat into tasks that can be completed and checked off. Execution, by contrast, is exposed. It involves reaching out, following up, and pushing conversations forward without guarantees. It requires resilience and patience. Over time, doing it yourself can become a coping mechanism. It fills effort and reduces anxiety,but it quietly undermines impact. Why "Faster" Is the Wrong Metric Speed is often measured at the task level: How quickly was the document written? How fast was the research completed? How soon was the report delivered? But economic development should measure speed at the decision and movement level: How quickly did the conversation advance? How soon did the next step occur? How long did momentum sustain? Task speed without execution speed is an illusion. A perfectly drafted document that sits unused creates no value. A good-enough draft that enables immediate action creates impact. The Bottleneck Effect When senior staff do everything themselves, they become the bottleneck,no matter how capable they are. Work piles up behind them. Decisions wait. Execution slows to the pace of the busiest person in the organization. This is not a leadership failure. It''s a structural one. Organizations that rely on their most experienced people to personally produce work limit their own capacity. They trade scalability for control, often without realizing it. Reframing Responsibility Less Work. More Impact requires a shift in how responsibility is defined. Responsibility is not: Writing every draft Touching every output Personally ensuring perfection Responsibility is: Ensuring the right work gets done Protecting high-impact execution Creating systems that move work forward Letting go of creation work is not abdication,it is leadership. The Cost in Burnout There is also a human cost to doing it yourself. Economic developers who carry too much creation work burn out faster. They feel constantly behind. Their days are filled with tasks, but their sense of progress diminishes. Over time, passion erodes. Frustration grows. The work becomes heavier than it needs to be. This isn''t because the job is impossible. It''s because the work mix is wrong. Putting a Dollar Value on Your Time Most economic developers understand, intellectually, that their time is valuable. But very few ever calculate it. And without a clear number, it becomes almost impossible to make confident decisions about when to delegate, when to invest in support, or when to stop doing something themselves. If you want to truly embrace Less Work. More Impact, you need to quantify your time, not abstractly, but practically. Step 1: Determine Your True Hourly Value Start with your total annual compensation. This includes: Salary Bonuses Benefits (estimated if needed) For simplicity, use your salary if that''s all you have. Now divide that number by 2,000 hours (a standard full-time work year). Example: $120,000 � 2,000 hours = $60/hour This gives you a baseline, but this number is misleading if taken at face value because you are not paid to perform every type of work. You are paid for high-impact work. Step 2: Adjust for Impact-Level Work In reality, only a portion of your time should be spent on the work that truly requires your expertise. Think about your role: Strategic conversations Relationship building Decision-making Project advancement This is your highest-value work. If only 25%�50% of your time should be spent here, then the value of that time is significantly higher. Adjusted Example: If $120,000 reflects only 50% of your true value-producing work: $120,000 � 1,000 hours = $120/hour If it''s closer to 25%: $120,000 � 500 hours = $240/hour This is your true impact rate. Step 3: Compare Task Value to Your Impact Rate Now apply this thinking to your daily work. Ask yourself: Should I be writing this first draft? Should I be researching this company? Should I be formatting this report? If a task can be completed by someone, or something, for $20, $30, or even $50/hour... but your impact rate is $120�$240/hour...you are operating at a loss. Not because the task isn''t important. But because you are the wrong person doing it. Step 4: The Buy Back Decision This leads to a simple decision framework: If the cost to delegate or automate a task is less than your impact rate, you should not be doing it. Every hour you reclaim can be reinvested into: Advancing projects Strengthening relationships Increasing follow-up consistency Creating momentum This is how time turns into impact. Step 5: Start Small, Then Expand You do not need to redesign everything at once. Start with just one category: First drafts Research Summaries Reports Buy back 5 hours per week. Then 10. Then 15. Over time, this compounds into: Faster execution More consistent outreach Greater strategic clarity And most importantly... More impact without working more hours. The Real Shift Buying back your time is not about spending money. It is about reallocating value. When you understand what your time is truly worth, the decision becomes clear: You stop asking, "Can I do this myself?" and start asking, "Should I?" Less Work. More Impact Requires Letting Go The first step toward Less Work. More Impact is recognizing that doing it yourself is often the most expensive option available. Not because it takes too long, but because it costs you the work only you can do. In the next chapter, we''ll explore Less Work. More Impact; not as a personal productivity hack, but as a leadership discipline, one that must be intentionally designed and protected. CHAPTER SIX Buying Back Time as a Leadership Discipline</p>'),
  ('ch6_title', 'Buying Back Time as a Leadership Discipline'),
  ('ch6_desc',  'Less Work.'),
  ('ch6_lead',  'Less Work.'),
  ('ch6_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch6_body',  '<p>Less Work. More Impact is not a productivity trick. It is a leadership discipline. Most economic development professionals think of managing their workload as a personal responsibility and something handled with better calendars, improved focus, or longer hours. But the most persistent challenges don''t come from individual habits. They come from how work is designed and distributed. Impact is not lost accidentally; it is shaped by the systems in place. When leaders fail to protect high-impact work intentionally, busywork fills the gap. Time Is an Organizational Asset In economic development, focus and capacity are among the most valuable assets an organization controls. They determine how quickly opportunities are pursued, how deeply relationships are built, and how consistently momentum is maintained. Yet these assets are rarely managed with the same rigor as budgets, staffing, or strategy. Meetings multiply without purpose. Creation work expands without limits. Responsiveness becomes a proxy for effectiveness. Over time, execution is squeezed into whatever space remains. Less Work. More Impact requires leaders to treat focus as a finite organizational resource--not a personal inconvenience. Leadership Sets the Work Mix Whether intentionally or not, leaders define what work is valued by what they reward, tolerate, and model. If leaders: Personally draft documents Respond instantly to every request Fix outputs instead of redesigning workflows They signal that creation matters more than execution. Staff follow suit. Less Work. More Impact requires leaders to explicitly redefine expectations around work. Designing for Leverage, Not Effort Leadership is not about doing more work; it''s about designing systems that allow the right work to happen consistently. This means asking questions like: Which tasks should never reach senior staff? Where does work slow unnecessarily? What activities consume effort without moving outcomes forward? Where are we relying on heroics instead of structure? These questions shift focus from effort to impact. Time Protection Is a Decision Focus does not protect itself. Less Work. More Impact requires intentional boundaries: Clear ownership of execution work Guardrails around creation tasks Systems that prevent low-value activity from escalating upward These boundaries are not about control. They are about clarity. From Personal Discipline to Organizational Design Personal productivity habits can help at the margins, but they cannot overcome poorly designed systems. Sustained impact comes from design, not effort. When Less Work. More Impact becomes a leadership discipline, organizations shift from reactive to intentional. Setting the Stage for New Models of Work Once leaders accept that creating more impact is their responsibility, new possibilities emerge. They begin to look for ways to: Standardize inputs Reduce first-draft work Accelerate preparation without sacrificing quality Free senior staff to focus on execution This is where new models of work become viable. In the next section of the book, we''ll explore one of the most powerful of those models: treating AI not as a tool, but as a trained workforce designed to absorb creative work and protect human judgment. CHAPTER SEVEN From Doing Everything Yourself to Relying on Specialists High-performing professionals do not succeed by doing</p>'),
  ('ch7_title', 'From Doing Everything Yourself to Relying on Specialists'),
  ('ch7_desc',  'everything themselves.'),
  ('ch7_lead',  'everything themselves.'),
  ('ch7_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch7_body',  '<p>everything themselves. They succeed by knowing where their focus creates the most impact, and by surrounding themselves with specialists everywhere else. This principle is obvious in elite performance environments, but it is far less obvious in economic development. A Lesson From the Field I played Division I baseball at Texas Tech and went on to pitch professionally in the minor leagues. Pitching was my strength. It''s where I created the most impact on the field; through preparation, execution, and mental discipline. I was also a good hitter, but it wasn''t my primary strength. So I didn''t pretend it was. I relied on specialist coaches. Hitting coaches helped refine mechanics, timing, and approach. These were areas where others had deeper expertise. Leaning on them didn''t make me less capable. It made me more effective by allowing me to focus on what I did best. Later, after my playing career, I spent more than twenty years coaching youth baseball. The lesson became even clearer from the other side of the dugout. A coach doesn''t win games by taking swings for players. A coach wins by preparing the team, setting strategy, correcting mistakes, and creating the conditions for execution. When a coach tries to play every position, the team loses structure, rhythm, and leverage. Economic development operates under the same dynamics. Capability Is Not the Same as Leverage Economic developers are often the most capable people in the room. They can write well. They can research thoroughly. They can prepare presentations, reports, and summaries. But capability does not equal impact. Just because someone can do a task does not mean they should be the one doing it. Especially when that task does not require their level of judgment or experience. In many organizations, the most capable professionals become the default creators. They write first drafts because they''re fast. They research because they know where to look. They prepare materials because they care about quality. Over time, this creates an invisible problem: the people best positioned to execute are trapped preparing to execute. The Specialist Advantage Specialists exist to absorb preparation so leaders can focus on execution. Preparation supports the work. It doesn''t drive the outcome. Economic development projects are not won by documents. They are won through persistence, timing, trust, and follow-through. Specialists protect that space. Leadership Means Stepping Back, Not Stepping In The most effective leaders resist the urge to step in simply because they can. They understand that doing everything themselves does not make them indispensable, it makes them a bottleneck. Leadership is not about proving competence. It is about designing leverage. Less Work. More Impact starts with a mindset shift: my role is not to do all the work, but to ensure the right work gets done. Why This Shift Matters Now Economic development has grown more complex, not less. Expectations are higher. Stakeholders are more numerous. Timelines are tighter. Trying to meet those demands by doing everything yourself is not sustainable. In the next chapter, we will explore how new models now make specialist-level support accessible without adding headcount, increasing payroll, or sacrificing control--and how economic development organizations can apply this model immediately. CHAPTER EIGHT Hiring Specialists Without the Cost If you''re like almost 80 percent of the economic development</p>'),
  ('ch8_title', 'Hiring Specialists Without the Cost'),
  ('ch8_desc',  'professionals I work with, your budget isn''t growing at all.'),
  ('ch8_lead',  'professionals I work with, your budget isn''t growing at all.'),
  ('ch8_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch8_body',  '<p>professionals I work with, your budget isn''t growing at all. It''s shrinking. At the same time, expectations are increasing. Boards, city managers, and elected officials want more outreach, more wins, more visibility, and more measurable results--often with fewer resources and less tolerance for delay. The pressure is clear: deliver more impact with fewer resources. More Pressure Doesn''t Create More Time Whether budgets are shrinking or merely tightening, the core constraint remains the same: focus and capacity. Reduced funding doesn''t reduce expectations. It compresses them. Without intentional redesign, this pressure forces senior professionals deeper into creation work at the exact moment execution matters most. Where Extra Dollars Create the Most Impact High-impact organizations prioritize investing in relationships, outreach, follow-up, strategy, and execution. They do not invest their most valuable resources in work that prepares for execution but does not execute itself. What''s Different Today Today, new technologies make specialist-level support accessible without adding headcount or increasing fixed costs. Preparation work, once absorbed by senior professionals, can now be handled quickly, consistently, and at scale. Execution Becomes the Focus Again When preparation work is handled efficiently, execution resurfaces. Senior professionals spend more time advancing conversations and applying judgment instead of preparing for the work. This is not about replacing people. It''s about respecting their focus and maximizing their impact. In the next chapter, we''ll examine the specific specialist roles that absorb the most effort--and how organizations can deploy modern solutions to support them immediately. CHAPTER NINE The Specialists Every Economic Development Organization Needs Once organizations accept that preparation work should not</p>'),
  ('ch9_title', 'The Specialists Every Economic Development Organization Needs'),
  ('ch9_desc',  'consume senior time, the next question becomes practical: What work should specialists actually handle?'),
  ('ch9_lead',  'consume senior time, the next question becomes practical: What work should specialists actually handle?'),
  ('ch9_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch9_body',  '<p>consume senior time, the next question becomes practical: What work should specialists actually handle? Across economic development organizations, the same categories of work repeatedly absorb effort, interrupt execution, and slow momentum. These are not strategic decisions. They are preparatory functions that exist to support judgment and action. Identifying these roles clearly is the first step toward creating more impact. Specialist #1: The Analysis Specialist Handles: SWOT analyses Industry overviews Competitive comparisons Workforce summaries Asset inventories When analysis is prepared consistently and quickly, leaders can focus on interpretation rather than data gathering. Specialist #2: The Research Specialist Handles: Company profiles, Industry context, Expansion signals, Market trends, Background preparation Prepared research accelerates outreach and follow-up. Specialist #3: The Communication Specialist Handles: Board updates and summaries Draft emails and follow-ups Talking points Project summaries Stakeholder messaging Prepared communication prevents senior staff from becoming bottlenecks. Specialist #4: The Preparation Specialist Handles: Meeting briefs Agenda outlines Presentation drafts Site visit materials Event preparation Preparation supports execution without consuming it. Specialist #5: The Documentation Specialist Handles: Meeting summaries Project updates Internal reports Status tracking Board-ready recaps Specialist support ensures documentation exists without dominating focus. Why These Roles Matter They ensure execution is not crowded out by preparation. When these roles are handled well, economic developers enter conversations prepared, follow up faster, and apply judgment more consistently. In the next chapter, we''ll explore how to deploy these specialists without disrupting existing workflows. CHAPTER TEN Deploying Specialists Without Disruption The biggest mistake organizations make when introducing new</p>'),
  ('ch10_title', 'Deploying Specialists Without Disruption'),
  ('ch10_desc',  'ways of working is trying to change everything at once.'),
  ('ch10_lead',  'ways of working is trying to change everything at once.'),
  ('ch10_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch10_body',  '<p>ways of working is trying to change everything at once. Economic development offices are busy, relationship-driven environments, and any model that requires a full reset, extensive retraining, or wholesale process changes will fail; no matter how good the idea is. Less Work. More Impact only works when it fits into how work already happens. That means specialists must integrate quietly, naturally, and immediately into existing workflows. Start Where Effort Is Already Being Lost Most economic developers can easily identify: Tasks they consistently push to evenings or weekends Work they postpone because it feels heavy Preparation they repeat over and over Drafting they wish they didn''t have to do These are the first places specialists belong. Specialists Should Enter Before Execution, Not After Specialists create the most leverage when they operate upstream, well before execution begins. That means: Research happens before outreach. Drafts exist before review. Summaries are ready before meetings, and background materials are prepared before conversations. Minimal Change, Maximum Impact Workflows remain the same. The difference is that preparation work no longer dominates the calendar. Adoption Happens Through Use, Not Training People don''t change their behavior because they attend a workshop; they change because something makes their work easier today. Leadership''s Role in Deployment The most powerful signal a leader can send is simple: "You don''t need to do that yourself anymore." Let the Model Prove Itself When one person stops working late, others notice. Momentum spreads organically. A Gradual Expansion One specialist becomes two. One use case becomes five. Preparation becomes faster across the organization. In the next chapter, we''ll explore what should never be offloaded--and why protecting certain responsibilities is just as important as delegating others. CHAPTER ELEVEN What Should Never Be Delegated In fact, the opposite is true. When preparation work is handled</p>'),
  ('ch11_title', 'What Should Never Be Delegated'),
  ('ch11_desc',  'efficiently, leaders have more capacity to focus on the responsibilities that truly require human judgment.'),
  ('ch11_lead',  'efficiently, leaders have more capacity to focus on the responsibilities that truly require human judgment.'),
  ('ch11_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch11_body',  '<p>efficiently, leaders have more capacity to focus on the responsibilities that truly require human judgment. But this only works if boundaries are clear. Judgment Cannot Be Delegated Decisions about incentives, partnerships, site selection, political considerations, and long-term strategy require context that goes beyond data. Specialists exist to inform judgment, not replace it. Relationships Are Always Human Trust is built through conversations, presence, credibility, and consistency. Preparation can support relationships, but relationships themselves must remain human. Accountability Stays With Leadership Leaders remain responsible for accuracy, tone, decisions, and outcomes. Specialists provide drafts. Leaders approve. Ethics and public trust cannot be outsourced. Economic development operates in public environments where transparency matters. Ethical guardrails must remain under human oversight. Strategy Is a Human Responsibility Strategy is an ongoing process of observation, adjustment, and decision-making. Specialists support strategy, but never define it. The Role of Specialists, Reaffirmed They reduce friction, improve consistency, and accelerate readiness. They do not make decisions, represent the organization, or own outcomes. In the next chapter, we''ll explore how to measure what truly matters. CHAPTER TWELVE Measuring What Actually Matters One of the biggest challenges in economic development is that the most important outcomes are often the hardest to measure.</p>'),
  ('ch12_title', 'Measuring What Actually Matters'),
  ('ch12_desc',  'Deals take time.'),
  ('ch12_lead',  'Deals take time.'),
  ('ch12_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch12_body',  '<p>Deals take time. Relationships compound quietly. Momentum builds long before results appear. As a result, organizations often fall back on measuring what is easy instead of what creates impact. Activity becomes a proxy for progress. Busyness becomes evidence of value. Less Work. More Impact requires a different approach. Why Traditional Metrics Fall Short Many organizations measure productivity through inputs: Number of meetings Number of emails sent Number of reports produced Number of events attended These metrics are easy to track, but they don''t tell the full story. High activity does not guarantee impact. It often masks inefficiency. The Shift From Activity to Impact Impact shows up as faster follow-up, better-prepared conversations, shorter time between steps, more consistent momentum, and higher-quality decisions. Measuring Focus Reclaimed Ask: How much effort is spent preparing versus executing? How often are senior professionals creating first drafts? Where has capacity reappeared? When preparation effort drops and execution focus rises, the system is working. Measuring Consistency Consistency shows up as regular follow-up, predictable preparation, and standardized outputs. Board-Ready Metrics That Matter Reduction in preparation effort, increase in outreach and follow-up focus, faster turnaround on board materials, improved responsiveness, and greater consistency in communication Measuring Momentum Momentum shows up as shorter gaps between steps, clearer ownership, and fewer stalled initiatives. Ultimately, success is not being busy. It is moving opportunities forward with greater impact. CHAPTER THIRTEEN Reclaiming the Work That Actually Matters Reclaiming the Work That Actually Matters</p>'),
  ('ch13_title', 'Reclaiming the Work That Actually Matters'),
  ('ch13_desc',  'When capacity is reclaimed, the change is not subtle.'),
  ('ch13_lead',  'When capacity is reclaimed, the change is not subtle.'),
  ('ch13_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch13_body',  '<p>When capacity is reclaimed, the change is not subtle. Economic developers don''t suddenly have less to do, but they have more focus to do the work that actually matters. The constant pressure to prepare, draft, and assemble begins to lift, and in its place something rare appears: space. That space is where impact lives. What Changes First The first thing most professionals notice is not a dramatic transformation; it''s relief. Preparation no longer dominates the day. Blank pages disappear. The sense of always being behind begins to fade. Work that once felt heavy becomes manageable. Then behavior starts to change. Calls are made sooner. Follow-ups happen more consistently. Meetings feel more purposeful. Execution moves from the margins to the center of the day. Returning to the Role You Were Hired For When preparation work is absorbed elsewhere, professionals reconnect with the work they were actually hired to do: Advancing conversations Building trust Navigating complexity Making decisions Creating momentum This shift restores both effectiveness and satisfaction. The Compounding Effect of Focus Focus compounds. When economic developers consistently spend time on execution, results begin to stack. Relationships deepen. Opportunities mature. Projects move through stages more predictably. Small improvements in follow-up and preparation quality lead to disproportionately large gains over time. Confidence Replaces Urgency When preparation is reliable and execution focus is protected, professionals no longer feel rushed. They respond thoughtfully instead of reactively. This confidence is felt by partners, prospects, and stakeholders. Rediscovering Strategic Thinking Strategic thinking requires space. Less Work. More Impact restores the ability to step back, evaluate patterns, and make intentional choices. A Healthier Way to Work Work feels lighter, not because expectations drop, but because effort is aligned with impact. The Ripple Effect When one person creates more impact with less effort, others notice. Teams begin to adopt similar habits. The culture shifts from busyness to purpose. In the next chapter, we''ll explore how this focus compounds over the long term. CHAPTER FOURTEEN The Compounding Effect of Focus Focus is one of the few advantages that compounds over time.</p>'),
  ('ch14_title', 'The Compounding Effect of Focus'),
  ('ch14_desc',  'In economic development, this compounding effect is often misunderstood because results are delayed.'),
  ('ch14_lead',  'In economic development, this compounding effect is often misunderstood because results are delayed.'),
  ('ch14_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch14_body',  '<p>In economic development, this compounding effect is often misunderstood because results are delayed. Projects take years. Relationships mature slowly. Wins appear sporadic on the surface. But underneath, momentum is either building or it isn''t. Less Work. More Impact changes the direction that momentum moves. Why Focus Beats Effort Over Time Most economic developers work hard. Effort is not the problem. The problem is fragmentation. When attention is constantly pulled into preparation, drafting, internal reporting, reactive emails, and last-minute materials, focus is broken into small, inefficient pieces. Even high effort produces limited impact when it is scattered. Execution requires continuity. A single strong conversation rarely creates a result. A single follow-up rarely builds trust. Momentum is built through sustained, intentional attention applied over time. When professionals consistently apply focus to execution--follow-up, relationship-building, decision-making, alignment--small actions begin to stack. Each conversation builds on the last. Each meeting advances instead of resets. Each decision compounds rather than delays. Over time, the difference becomes dramatic. The Mathematics of Compounding Attention Compounding does not require dramatic change. It requires consistency. If a prospect hears from you consistently instead of sporadically, trust increases. If stakeholders receive clarity instead of rushed updates, alignment improves. If follow-ups happen in days instead of weeks, momentum accelerates. None of these changes look revolutionary on a weekly report. But over months and years, they separate high-impact organizations from those that remain stuck in cycles of activity without progress. Compounding focus is not flashy. It is disciplined. The Hidden Cost of Fragmentation Distraction doesn''t just slow progress, it erodes it. When economic developers are forced to repeatedly shift between execution and preparation, context is lost. Energy drains. Nuance disappears. Conversations restart instead of advancing. Over time, this creates misleading narratives: "Deals are just taking longer." "The market is tougher than it used to be." "Prospects aren''t as responsive." Sometimes those things are true. But often, focus has been diluted. Less Work. More Impact restores continuity--the ability to stay with an opportunity long enough to move it forward with intention instead of interruption. Strategic Capacity Expands As focus compounds, something unexpected happens: strategic capacity expands. When leaders are no longer buried in daily creation work, they begin to see patterns earlier. They recognize weak signals. They notice misalignment before it becomes a conflict. They adjust positioning before opportunities cool. Strategy stops being something discussed at annual retreats and becomes something practiced in real time. Focus creates perspective. Perspective improves decisions. Better decisions accelerate outcomes. That is compounding at work. The Long-Term Advantage Over months and years, organizations that protect focus begin to separate themselves. They are more responsive. Not because they are frantic, but because they are prepared. They are more consistent. Not because they work longer, but because they protect attention. They are easier to work with, because they follow through. What looks like efficiency in the short term becomes resilience in the long term. Resilience is not built through intensity. It is built through sustained clarity. Staying Ahead of Change Economic development is not static. Technologies change. Markets shift. Incentive structures evolve. Political expectations fluctuate. Organizations operating at full capacity, simply trying to keep up, have no room to adapt. Those that create more impact create intentional space--not idle time, but strategic slack. That space allows them to experiment, evaluate new tools, refine outreach strategies, and adjust positioning before external pressure forces a reaction. They move from reactive to anticipatory. And anticipatory organizations win. Focus as a Leadership Discipline Focus is not a personality trait. It is not about temperament or preference. It is a leadership discipline. It requires choosing what receives attention, and what does not. It requires protecting execution focus even when preparation feels urgent. It requires designing systems that support continuity instead of constant interruption. Less Work. More Impact makes that discipline sustainable. The compounding effect of focus does not show up overnight. It builds quietly, steadily, and decisively. Organizations that commit to it today position themselves for long-term impact; not just next quarter''s activity. In the next chapter, we''ll examine how this shift fundamentally reshapes the role of the economic developer--and why that evolution is essential for the future of the profession. CHAPTER FIFTEEN The Evolving Role of the Economic Developer The role of the economic developer is changing. Not because the</p>'),
  ('ch15_title', 'The Evolving Role of the Economic Developer'),
  ('ch15_desc',  'mission has changed.'),
  ('ch15_lead',  'mission has changed.'),
  ('ch15_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch15_body',  '<p>mission has changed. But because the environment has. Communities still compete for investment, talent, and opportunity. Projects still require alignment, negotiation, and trust. But the pace of information, the expectations of stakeholders, and the complexity of decision-making have accelerated. The traditional model, where one person acts as researcher, writer, coordinator, strategist, and closer, is no longer sustainable. Less Work. More Impact is not just about productivity. It is about evolution. From Generalist to Strategic Orchestrator Historically, economic developers operated as highly capable generalists. They wore multiple hats and filled gaps wherever needed. That flexibility was an advantage in smaller teams and simpler environments. Today, the volume and velocity of work have outpaced that model. The modern economic developer must shift from being the primary producer of work to being the orchestrator of work. An orchestrator: Sets direction. Protects priorities. Ensures preparation happens. Applies judgment at key decision points. Maintains momentum across stakeholders. They do not personally generate every input. They ensure the right inputs exist. This distinction changes everything. Judgment Becomes the Scarce Resource Information is no longer scarce. Focus is. Judgment is. As access to research, data, and drafting support increases, the differentiator becomes interpretation. Which signals matter? Which prospects deserve attention now? Which incentives align with long-term strategy? Which partnerships create leverage instead of complexity? These questions require experience and context. They cannot be automated. They cannot be outsourced. And they cannot be answered well when attention is fragmented. Less Work. More Impact protects judgment. Visibility Over Volume In the past, productivity was often measured by visible output; reports, presentations, activity logs. The future belongs to professionals who create clarity, not volume. Clarity in: Communication Priorities Next steps Expectations When economic developers operate with clarity, boards gain confidence. Stakeholders align faster. Prospects experience consistency. Clarity scales. Volume does not. The Shift From Reactive to Designed Work Without intentional design, economic development becomes reactive. Emails dictate priorities. Requests override strategy. Urgency replaces importance. The evolved economic developer designs their work environment. They: Define what requires their involvement. Establish guardrails around preparation. Create repeatable workflows. Protect execution focus They do not allow busyness to dictate value. A Profession at an Inflection Point Economic development is at an inflection point. Those who cling to the identity of "the one who does it all" will find themselves increasingly overwhelmed. Those who embrace leverage, who design systems, deploy specialists, and protect judgment, will operate at a different level. The difference will not be subtle. It will show up in momentum. In confidence. In results. Leading the Shift This evolution will not happen accidentally. It requires leadership. Leadership that: Acknowledges the impact of the problem. Rejects the badge of busyness. Redefines productivity. Protects execution Less Work. More Impact is the mechanism. But the outcome is transformation. In the final chapter, we will bring these ideas together into a practical framework you can begin applying immediately--so that this book does not sit on a shelf, but reshapes how you work. CHAPTER SIXTEEN A Practical Framework for Less Work. More Impact Ideas only matter if they change behavior.</p>'),
  ('ch16_title', 'A Practical Framework for Less Work. More Impact'),
  ('ch16_desc',  'Less Work.'),
  ('ch16_lead',  'Less Work.'),
  ('ch16_time',  '5 min read'),
  ('ch16_body',  '<p>Less Work. More Impact is not a philosophy to admire. It is a discipline to implement. If this book is going to reshape how you work, it must translate into specific actions--starting now. What follows is a practical framework you can apply immediately. Step 1: Conduct a Focus Audit For two weeks, track your work in simple categories: Execution | Preparation | Administration | Distraction Do not overcomplicate this. A notebook or simple spreadsheet is enough. At the end of two weeks, review the pattern. Most professionals discover that preparation consumes far more effort than they realized. Awareness is the starting point. Step 2: Identify "Only You" Work List the tasks that genuinely require your judgment, relationships, or authority. These typically include: High-stakes conversations. Negotiations. Strategic decisions. Stakeholder alignment. Critical follow-up Everything else is a candidate for redesign. If someone else, or something else, can create the first draft, gather the data, or structure the material, it does not belong in your primary focus block. Step 3: Eliminate Before You Shift Before assigning work elsewhere, ask: Does this need to exist at all? Is this report required--or assumed? Is this meeting advancing something--or maintaining optics? Is this level of detail necessary? Elimination creates more impact than shifting work alone. Step 4: Standardize What Repeats Many "time drains" exist because work is reinvented each time. Create: Templates. Checklists. Standard briefing formats. Repeatable outreach structures Standardization reduces decision fatigue and accelerates preparation. Step 5: Deploy Specialists Strategically Identify the 3�5 preparation tasks that consistently consume your effort. Common examples: First drafts of board updates, Company background research. Meeting summaries. Presentation outlines. Industry overviews These are your leverage points. Whether through internal support, structured systems, or AI specialists, shift those responsibilities away from your core execution hours. Start small. Prove relief. Expand gradually. Step 6: Protect Execution Focus Block time on your calendar for execution--and defend it. During execution blocks: No drafting. No internal formatting. No reactive inbox management Use this time for: Follow-up calls. Strategic conversations. Relationship building. Advancing active projects Execution must be intentional. It will not happen by accident. Step 7: Measure Movement, Not Activity Shift your metrics. Track: Speed of follow-up. Time between project steps. Consistency of outreach. Clarity of next actions Do not confuse busyness with progress. Momentum is the real metric. Step 8: Reassess Quarterly Every quarter, revisit: What work has crept back onto your plate? Where are you defaulting to first drafts again? What new preparation tasks can be shifted? Less Work. More Impact is not a one-time reset. It is an ongoing leadership discipline.</p>')
